Vatapá

Vatapá is a dish originating from [Brazil](/Brazil). Its primary ingredients consist of [bread](/Bread), [shrimp](/Shrimp_and_prawn_as_food), [coconut milk](/Coconut_milk), finely ground [peanuts](/Peanut), and [palm oil](/Palm_oil), all mashed together to form a creamy paste. This culinary creation is particularly emblematic of [Salvador, Bahia](/Salvador,_Bahia) and is also a prevalent dish in the [North](/North_Region,_Brazil) and [Northeast](/Northeast_Region,_Brazil) regions of Brazil. Within the northeastern state of [Bahia](/Bahia), it is frequently served alongside [acarajé](/Acaraj%C3%A9) and holds a significant role as a ritual offering in [Candomblé](/Candombl%C3%A9) ceremonies, often presented with [acaçá](/Aca%C3%A7%C3%A1) or acarajé. In other parts of Brazil, Vatapá is commonly enjoyed with [white rice](/White_rice). The use of shrimp in the dish is not absolute; they can be substituted with alternative ingredients to suit different preferences or availability.

### Etymology

The name "Vatapá" is believed to derive from the [Yoruba](/Yoruba_language) term *vata'pa*. The phonetic pronunciation is rendered as [vɐtɐˈpa&#93;](/Help:IPA/Portuguese).

### Origin

The origins of Vatapá are rooted in [Africa](/Africa), having been introduced to Brazil by the [Yoruba people](/Yoruba_people). They brought with them a dish known as *ehba-tápa*, which is considered the precursor to the modern Vatapá. This dish has become a cornerstone of northeastern Brazilian cuisine, particularly in the state of [Bahia](/Bahia), where *dendê* (unrefined red [palm oil](/Palm_oil)) is an indispensable component. In Bahia, it is almost always presented with [caruru](/Caruru_(food)).

### In Popular Culture

The allure of Vatapá has transcended the culinary realm, finding its way into Brazilian music. In 1957, the renowned Brazilian songwriter [Dorival Caymmi](/Dorival_Caymmi) composed a song titled "Vatapá," which, intriguingly, weaves the recipe for the dish into its lyrics, outlining the key ingredients and offering rudimentary preparation guidance. This musical tribute was later reinterpreted by the celebrated singer [Gal Costa](/Gal_Costa) on her album *Gal Canta Caymmi* (1976), a collection dedicated to Caymmi's compositions.

Furthermore, Vatapá is referenced in Caymmi's 1941 composition, "[Você Já Foi à Bahia?](/Voc%C3%AA_J%C3%A1_Foi_%C3%A0_Bahia%3F)" (translating to "Have You Been to Bahia?"). In this song, alongside caruru and [munguzá](/Munguz%C3%A1), Vatapá is highlighted as a quintessential Bahian specialty. A partial adaptation of this song was featured in the 1944 film *[The Three Caballeros](/The_Three_Caballeros)*, a production by [Walt Disney](/Walt_Disney). Within the film, the character [José Carioca](/Jos%C3%A9_Carioca) sings this version in an effort to entice [Donald Duck](/Donald_Duck) to journey to Bahia.

